<h2>Filters</h2>

<p>Filters can be applied value displayed in the textbox. For more information about filters, see the filters section of the Data Quality documentation.</p>

<p>Note: The <code>Trim</code> filter is applied on all textboxes by default.</p>

<p>Example with an uppercase filter set:</p>
<div class="bs-docs-example">
    <d-formspy class="form-horizontal">
        <f-textbox label="name" filter="Uppercase" value="John Smith"></f-textbox>
    </d-formspy>
</div>

<pre class="prettyprint linenums">
{% set textboxExample5 %}
<f-textbox label="name" filter="Uppercase" value="John Smith"></f-textbox>{% endset %}{{textboxExample5|e}}
</pre>

<p>Set a filter chain:</p>
<div class="bs-docs-example">
    <d-formspy class="form-horizontal">
        <f-textbox label="name" filter='["Trim", "Uppercase"]' value="    John Smith    "></f-textbox>
    </d-formspy>
</div>

<pre class="prettyprint linenums">
{% set textboxExample6 %}
<f-textbox label="name" filter='["Trim", "Uppercase"]' value="    John Smith    "></f-textbox>{% endset %}{{textboxExample6|e}}
</pre>

<p>Filters are created by <a href="api/havok/filter/factory.html">havok/filter/factory</a> which supports abreviated names for the filters bundled with havok. To set your own custom filter, pass the complete module name. Eg <code>filters: 'My/Filter/Module'</code></p>

